    "abstract": "<jats:p> Betas from return regressions are commonly used to measure systematic financial market risks. \u201cGood\u201d beta measurements are essential for a range of empirical inquiries in finance and macroeconomics. We introduce a novel econometric framework for the nonparametric estimation of time-varying betas with high-frequency data. The \u201clocal Gaussian\u201d property of the generic continuous-time benchmark model enables optimal \u201cfinite-sample\u201d inference in a well-defined sense. It also affords more reliable inference in empirically realistic settings compared to conventional large-sample approaches. Two applications pertaining to the tracking performance of leveraged ETFs and an intraday event study illustrate the practical usefulness of the new procedures. (JEL C22, C58, G12, G23) </jats:p>",
